and ethnic considerations. Dávila scrutinizes dramatic shifts in housing, the growth of charter schools, and the enactment of Empowerment Zone legislation that promises upward mobility and empowerment while shutting out many longtime residents. Foregrounding privatization and consumption, she offers an innovative look at the marketing of Latino space. She emphasizes class among Latinos while touching on black-Latino and Mexican-Puerto Rican relations. Providing a unique multifaceted view of the place of Latinos in the changing urban landscape, Barrio Dreams is one of the most nuanced and original examinations of the complex social and economic forces shaping our cities today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnterprise zoneszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aGentrificationzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aHousing policyzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aLatin AmericansxHousingzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aLatin AmericansxHousingzUnited States. 0aPuerto RicansxHousingzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aUrban developmentzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aUrbanizationzNew York (State)zNew York. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aamerican culture.  aamerican legislation.  acharter schools.  aclass differences.  aconsumption.  acultural politics.  ademographic studies.  aeconomic empowerment.  ael barrio.  aethnic issues.  agentrification.  aglobalization.  ahousing crises.  aimmigrant experience.  ainterethnic relations.  alargest minority group.  alatinization.  alatinos.  aneoliberals.  anew york.  anonfiction.  apuerto ricans.  aracial issues.  asociology.  aspanish harlem.  atextbooks.  aurban landscape.  aurban space.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook p